>>890839598
As an addendum to otheranon's reply, you could try lowering the weight of the celebrity's name, such as (famous person:0.7). My understanding of the way this shit works is it builds a baseline understanding of an average for "human face" and then when a celebrity's face is learned, it is learned in mathematical calculations that show how it differs from that average face, so when you prompt using a celebrity's name, sometimes you get something like a caricature. Angelina Jolie has plump lips, which might sometimes look cartoonish when rendered by the software. (She may work fine, given she probably has more images of her in the dataset than most other female celebrities). So, turning down the weight on the name can help with a more realistic output. Start at 1.0, and playing with going down (or up) in .1 increments.

posts.com:
Can you imagine what it's like to be a bat?
Of course, you can construct a basic image, based on what we know, but you will never know what it FEELS like. The intricacies of bat-ness are completely out of your reach, as you've never been a bat, nor will you ever be a bat.

This shows the idea that the only thing you know what it feels like to be is yourself.

The conclusion I'm reaching to is that not a single person on this planet can understand the intricacies of what it's like to be someone else. These intricacies would naturally be compounded the more different someone is from you.

Men and women are about as different as it's possible for humans to be. A man will never know what it's like to be a woman. No matter how much estrogen, how many surgeries, how much make-up, or whathaveyou. The reverse is also true.

This is why we see so many transgender caricatures of women. They think they're a woman, but they don't know what it is to be a woman, so they act the way they believe women are, resulting in a caricature.
